<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-621-267  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 621 267.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 19 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Moscow: two exchanges to launch comm satellite.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tchashchin, Kirill.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsSoviet UnionCommoditiesCommunications EquipmentRussian Commodities and Raw Materials Exchange.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MOSCOW: TWO EXCHANGES TO LAUNCH COMM SATELLITE 11/19/90 MOSCOW, U.S.S.R.,andO;1990 NOV 19 (NB) -- The Moscow-based Russian (formerly Moscow) Commoditiesand Raw Materials Exchange and Stock Exchange agreed to launch their owncommunications satellite to ease relaions with their peers across thecountry.andM;Mr.andP;  Sergey Petrov, telecommunications manager of the Commodities exchangetold Newsbytes that they reached an agreement with the Soviet space ministryand other regulatory authorities to design, build and launch a satellitewithin the next two years.andP;  The new satellite is expected to providecommunication facilities capable of handling the mostly data traffic betweenthe Moscow exchanges and their subsidiaries throughout the country.andM;Mr.andP;  Petrov said that despite some early announcements that this satellitewill cost 67 millions roubles, it's very difficult to pinpoint so precise aprice at the moment.andM;The Soviet Space control center based close to Moscow has also agreed also toprovide the exchanges with 20,000 existing satellite phone channels that areavailable immediately, Mr. Petrov said.andM;(Kirill Tchashchin/19901118/Press contact: Sergey Perov, Russian Commodityexchange, phone +7 095 924-7530 fax +7 095 262-5757)</TEXT></DOC>